frameDefinitions: An Agent has placed a Theme in an accessible but somewhat out of the way Location for the purposes of maintaining it free from harm and illegitimate use while it is not being used.

These words describe the recovery or healing of a Patient from an Affliction without reference to the influence of any Treatment or Healer (see the Cure frame).  '' 'My injuries had not yet completely healed.'
In this frame an Agent continues to possess a Theme for a Duration of time. '' 'In her heart she must retain bitterness against those who had killed him.'
The Authorities hold a Suspect under suspicion of having committed a crime (Charges).
In this frame a Container holds within its physical boundaries the Contents.
An Agent causes a Dryee (either a surface or an entire entity, inside and out) to become dry.
frameExamples: My injuries had not yet completely <t>healed</t>.
In her heart she must <t>retain</t> bitterness against those who had killed him.
The police <t>held</t> Mr. Smith in the slammer on charges of killing his lawyer.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person who has placed the <fen>Theme</fen> in the <fen>Location</fen>.
The <fen>Theme</fen> is the object that is kept in a <fen>Location</fen> by the <fen>Agent</fen>
The location where the <fen>Theme</fen> is kept. Some, though not all, LUs in this frame incorporate this FE.
<fen>Time</fen> is the time period during which the <fen>Theme</fen> is stored.
The <fen>Place</fen> indicates where the Storing occurs.
The    Patient may either be expressed as the External Argument or, as in Health.Cure, may occur as the possessor of the Affliction (an example of role conflation):
This role is the injury, pain or disease experienced by the Patient.  Affliction occurs either as an External Argument of verbs or as a PP Complement of nouns or verbs:
Where Body Part is expressed as a separate constituent (rather than in phrases such as <ment>the wound on Pat's arm</ment>), it occurs as an External Argument:
The time at which the recovery takes place.
The location where the recovery takes place.
The person who has possession of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The entity which the <fen>Agent</fen> possesses for a <fen>Duration</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Agent</fen> has possession of the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The location where the <fen>Agent</fen> keeps the <fen>Theme</fen>.
The <fen>Authorities</fen> hold the <fen>Suspect</fen> in custody.
This role identifies the person who is taken into custody and held, under suspicion of having committed a crime.
When the detaining occurs.
Where the detaining takes place.
The <fen>Container</fen> is the physical object which holds within its boundaries the <fen>Contents</fen>
The <fen>Contents</fen> is the substance or objects contained within the physical bounds of the <fen>Container</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Container</fen> holds the <fen>Contents</fen>.
The <fen>Agent</fen> is the person performing the intentional act causing the <fen>Dryee</fen> to become dry.
The <fen>Dryee</fen> is the entity which has the water removed from it.
An animate or inanimate entity, a force, or event that produces the state of dryness. Volitionality is not a necessary characteristic of <fen>Cause</fen>s.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Agent</fen> intentionally affects the <fen>Dryee</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Agent</fen> intentionally affects the <fen>Dryee</fen>.
listRoleExamples: At all times <fex>the Saxon government</fex> held on to its insistently practiced political tradition.
Once you've got a War Bond, hang on to <fex>it</fex> for the full ten years of its life.
Margerite held on to the key <fex>on Wednesday</fex> until I returned to pick it up.
He will retain <fex>in his heart</fex> the memory of the vast Holocaust.
